/**
 * @page cutscene_authoring_guide How To Script A Cutscene
 * @tableofcontents
 *
 * @section cutscene_authoring_shape File Shape
 *
 * Cutscenes are section-based text files parsed by @ref CutsceneFormat and run
 * by @ref CutsceneRunner.
 *
 * Required sections:
 * - `[header]`
 * - `[steps]`
 *
 * Example:
 * @code{.ini}
 * [header]
 * id|example_cutscene
 *
 * [steps]
 * move|player|5|5
 * move|some_npc|3|5
 * sync
 * face|some_npc|right
 * say|Some NPC|Hello there!;Welcome to this example cutscene.
 * wait|60
 * flag|example_done
 * @endcode
 *
 * @section cutscene_authoring_commands Commands
 *
 * Supported commands:
 * - `move|target|x|y`
 * - `walk|target|direction`
 * - `face|target|direction`
 * - `say|speaker|line1;line2`
 * - `wait|frames`
 * - `sync`
 * - `flag|name`
 * - `hide|npc_id`
 * - `show|npc_id`
 *
 * Targets are either `player` or an NPC id from the active map.
 *
 * @section cutscene_authoring_tips Authoring Tips
 *
 * Practical rules that make scripts easier to maintain:
 * - Queue parallel movement with multiple `move` or `walk` commands, then end
 *   the sequence with `sync`.
 * - Use event flags to make one-shot scenes non-repeatable.
 * - Keep dialogue ownership clear by using consistent speaker names.
 * - Prefer small cutscenes that do one story job well over large monolithic
 *   scene files.
 *
 * `assets/data/cutscenes/example.cutscene` is the best starting reference when
 * authoring a new script.
 */
